</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Noninvasive imaging is an important screening and diagnostic tool in conditions associated with sudden cardiac death. The most common cause of sudden cardiac death is coronary artery disease, with myocarditis, cardiac sarcoidosis, and dilated and infiltrative cardiomyopathies being less common acquired causes. Common risk factors for sudden cardiac death, regardless of the disease process, include severe ventricular dysfunction and the presence of macroscopic scar seen at delayed contrast material–enhanced imaging. Recent advances in electrocardiographically (ECG) gated cardiac magnetic resonance (MR) imaging and multidetector computed tomography (CT) have led to increased referrals for cross-sectional imaging; thus, cardiac radiologists should be familiar with the disease entities associated with sudden cardiac death. Inflammatory processes and cardiomyopathies are best depicted with cardiac MR imaging. Steady-state free precession cine sequences coupled with inversion-recovery prepared gradient-echo T1-weighted sequences performed after the intravenous administration of gadolinium-based contrast material should form the basis of cardiac MR imaging protocols for cardiomyopathy. A clinical history that is suggestive of myocardial ischemia, specific requests to exclude coronary artery disease, or contraindications for MR imaging may imply that multidetector CT would be more appropriate. Nevertheless, both cardiac MR imaging and ECG-gated multidetector CT offer robust diagnosis and risk stratification for individual disease processes associated with sudden cardiac death.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.293085715">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.293085715">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g01a.jpeg" height="1619" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1a.</b>  Multivessel stenosis in a 60-year-old man with worsening angina on mild exertion. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced ECG-gated multidetector CT scan shows severe ostial plaque affecting the left main coronary artery (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Left anterior oblique curved reformatted image shows the ostial lesion (arrow), along with additional focal stenosis of the proximal left anterior descending coronary artery (arrowhead). The lesions were estimated to cause diameter reductions of approximately 65% and 70%, respectively. <b>(c, d)</b> Invasive coronary angiograms help confirm 70% stenosis of the left main coronary artery (arrow in <b>c</b>) and 60%–70% stenosis of the mid–left anterior descending coronary artery (arrow in <b>d</b>). The patient subsequently underwent urgent four-vessel coronary artery bypass grafting.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F1A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g01b.jpeg" height="1651" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1b.</b>  Multivessel stenosis in a 60-year-old man with worsening angina on mild exertion. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced ECG-gated multidetector CT scan shows severe ostial plaque affecting the left main coronary artery (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Left anterior oblique curved reformatted image shows the ostial lesion (arrow), along with additional focal stenosis of the proximal left anterior descending coronary artery (arrowhead). The lesions were estimated to cause diameter reductions of approximately 65% and 70%, respectively. <b>(c, d)</b> Invasive coronary angiograms help confirm 70% stenosis of the left main coronary artery (arrow in <b>c</b>) and 60%–70% stenosis of the mid–left anterior descending coronary artery (arrow in <b>d</b>). The patient subsequently underwent urgent four-vessel coronary artery bypass grafting.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F1B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g01c.jpeg" height="1641" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1c.</b>  Multivessel stenosis in a 60-year-old man with worsening angina on mild exertion. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced ECG-gated multidetector CT scan shows severe ostial plaque affecting the left main coronary artery (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Left anterior oblique curved reformatted image shows the ostial lesion (arrow), along with additional focal stenosis of the proximal left anterior descending coronary artery (arrowhead). The lesions were estimated to cause diameter reductions of approximately 65% and 70%, respectively. <b>(c, d)</b> Invasive coronary angiograms help confirm 70% stenosis of the left main coronary artery (arrow in <b>c</b>) and 60%–70% stenosis of the mid–left anterior descending coronary artery (arrow in <b>d</b>). The patient subsequently underwent urgent four-vessel coronary artery bypass grafting.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F1C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g01d.jpeg" height="1661" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1d.</b>  Multivessel stenosis in a 60-year-old man with worsening angina on mild exertion. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced ECG-gated multidetector CT scan shows severe ostial plaque affecting the left main coronary artery (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Left anterior oblique curved reformatted image shows the ostial lesion (arrow), along with additional focal stenosis of the proximal left anterior descending coronary artery (arrowhead). The lesions were estimated to cause diameter reductions of approximately 65% and 70%, respectively. <b>(c, d)</b> Invasive coronary angiograms help confirm 70% stenosis of the left main coronary artery (arrow in <b>c</b>) and 60%–70% stenosis of the mid–left anterior descending coronary artery (arrow in <b>d</b>). The patient subsequently underwent urgent four-vessel coronary artery bypass grafting.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F1D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g02a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1412" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  Multivessel stenosis in a 73-year-old man with chest pain on moderate exertion. Stress echocardiography, which had elicited inducible circumflex territory ischemia, was terminated due to nonsustained ventricular tachycardia. <b>(a)</b> Axial ECG-gated multidetector CT scan shows multifocal plaque in the left main and left anterior descending coronary arteries. However, these findings were not thought to be severe. <b>(b, c)</b> Oblique curved reformatted images show multifocal stenosis and occlusion of the midcircumflex artery immediately distal to the first obtuse marginal branch (arrows in <b>b</b>) and significant stenosis of the distal right and posterior descending coronary arteries (arrowheads in <b>c</b>). <b>(d, e)</b> Anterior oblique invasive angiographic images of the left <b>(d)</b> and right <b>(e)</b> coronary arteries help confirm the cardiac multidetector CT findings of an occluded circumflex artery (arrow in <b>d</b>) and two separate eccentric stenoses in the right coronary artery (arrows in <b>e</b>). The patient underwent successful percutaneous stent placement in the right coronary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g02b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1368" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  Multivessel stenosis in a 73-year-old man with chest pain on moderate exertion. Stress echocardiography, which had elicited inducible circumflex territory ischemia, was terminated due to nonsustained ventricular tachycardia. <b>(a)</b> Axial ECG-gated multidetector CT scan shows multifocal plaque in the left main and left anterior descending coronary arteries. However, these findings were not thought to be severe. <b>(b, c)</b> Oblique curved reformatted images show multifocal stenosis and occlusion of the midcircumflex artery immediately distal to the first obtuse marginal branch (arrows in <b>b</b>) and significant stenosis of the distal right and posterior descending coronary arteries (arrowheads in <b>c</b>). <b>(d, e)</b> Anterior oblique invasive angiographic images of the left <b>(d)</b> and right <b>(e)</b> coronary arteries help confirm the cardiac multidetector CT findings of an occluded circumflex artery (arrow in <b>d</b>) and two separate eccentric stenoses in the right coronary artery (arrows in <b>e</b>). The patient underwent successful percutaneous stent placement in the right coronary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g02c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1684" aria-labelledby="F2C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2c.</b>  Multivessel stenosis in a 73-year-old man with chest pain on moderate exertion. Stress echocardiography, which had elicited inducible circumflex territory ischemia, was terminated due to nonsustained ventricular tachycardia. <b>(a)</b> Axial ECG-gated multidetector CT scan shows multifocal plaque in the left main and left anterior descending coronary arteries. However, these findings were not thought to be severe. <b>(b, c)</b> Oblique curved reformatted images show multifocal stenosis and occlusion of the midcircumflex artery immediately distal to the first obtuse marginal branch (arrows in <b>b</b>) and significant stenosis of the distal right and posterior descending coronary arteries (arrowheads in <b>c</b>). <b>(d, e)</b> Anterior oblique invasive angiographic images of the left <b>(d)</b> and right <b>(e)</b> coronary arteries help confirm the cardiac multidetector CT findings of an occluded circumflex artery (arrow in <b>d</b>) and two separate eccentric stenoses in the right coronary artery (arrows in <b>e</b>). The patient underwent successful percutaneous stent placement in the right coronary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F2C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g02d.jpeg" height="1690" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2d.</b>  Multivessel stenosis in a 73-year-old man with chest pain on moderate exertion. Stress echocardiography, which had elicited inducible circumflex territory ischemia, was terminated due to nonsustained ventricular tachycardia. <b>(a)</b> Axial ECG-gated multidetector CT scan shows multifocal plaque in the left main and left anterior descending coronary arteries. However, these findings were not thought to be severe. <b>(b, c)</b> Oblique curved reformatted images show multifocal stenosis and occlusion of the midcircumflex artery immediately distal to the first obtuse marginal branch (arrows in <b>b</b>) and significant stenosis of the distal right and posterior descending coronary arteries (arrowheads in <b>c</b>). <b>(d, e)</b> Anterior oblique invasive angiographic images of the left <b>(d)</b> and right <b>(e)</b> coronary arteries help confirm the cardiac multidetector CT findings of an occluded circumflex artery (arrow in <b>d</b>) and two separate eccentric stenoses in the right coronary artery (arrows in <b>e</b>). The patient underwent successful percutaneous stent placement in the right coronary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F2D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g02e.jpeg" height="1662" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2e.</b>  Multivessel stenosis in a 73-year-old man with chest pain on moderate exertion. Stress echocardiography, which had elicited inducible circumflex territory ischemia, was terminated due to nonsustained ventricular tachycardia. <b>(a)</b> Axial ECG-gated multidetector CT scan shows multifocal plaque in the left main and left anterior descending coronary arteries. However, these findings were not thought to be severe. <b>(b, c)</b> Oblique curved reformatted images show multifocal stenosis and occlusion of the midcircumflex artery immediately distal to the first obtuse marginal branch (arrows in <b>b</b>) and significant stenosis of the distal right and posterior descending coronary arteries (arrowheads in <b>c</b>). <b>(d, e)</b> Anterior oblique invasive angiographic images of the left <b>(d)</b> and right <b>(e)</b> coronary arteries help confirm the cardiac multidetector CT findings of an occluded circumflex artery (arrow in <b>d</b>) and two separate eccentric stenoses in the right coronary artery (arrows in <b>e</b>). The patient underwent successful percutaneous stent placement in the right coronary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F2E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g03x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3.</b>  Arrhythmogenic focus in a 79-year-old man with coronary artery disease and previous anteroseptal non-ST-elevated myocardial infarction who had experienced numerous syncopal episodes. A Holter monitor demonstrated premature ventricular contractions with alternating left and right bundle branch block morphologic features, findings that were suggestive of a high septal origin for the arrhythmia. Short-axis oblique inversion-recovery prepared gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows a culprit area of focal infarction in the subaortic interventricular septum (arrow). The patient subsequently underwent successful ablation of the arrhythmogenic focus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g04a.jpeg" height="1536" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  Multivessel stenosis in a 75-year-old man who presented with congestive heart failure and syncope. The patient had experienced myocardial infarction 8 years earlier. An electrophysiologic study induced sustained monomorphic ventricular tachycardia requiring cardioversion. <b>(a)</b> Axial SSFP cine image shows severe thinning of the apical septum and apex consistent with an aneurysm. <b>*</b> indicates adherent thrombus within the ventricular lumen. <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis <b>(b)</b> and left anterior <b>(c)</b> oblique two-chamber inversion-recovery prepared gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images show extensive transmural enhancement involving the entire apex and anterior wall (arrows), a finding that is indicative of prior myocardial infarction. The scar burden constituted 35% of the total left ventricular mass, and the left ventricular ejection fraction was 19%. <b>*</b> indicates adherent thrombus within the ventricular lumen (cf <b>a</b>). Invasive coronary angiography showed 90% and 70% stenosis of the proximal left anterior descending and right coronary arteries, respectively. The patient subsequently underwent successful coronary artery bypass grafting and left ventricular aneurysmectomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g04b.jpeg" height="1551" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  Multivessel stenosis in a 75-year-old man who presented with congestive heart failure and syncope. The patient had experienced myocardial infarction 8 years earlier. An electrophysiologic study induced sustained monomorphic ventricular tachycardia requiring cardioversion. <b>(a)</b> Axial SSFP cine image shows severe thinning of the apical septum and apex consistent with an aneurysm. <b>*</b> indicates adherent thrombus within the ventricular lumen. <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis <b>(b)</b> and left anterior <b>(c)</b> oblique two-chamber inversion-recovery prepared gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images show extensive transmural enhancement involving the entire apex and anterior wall (arrows), a finding that is indicative of prior myocardial infarction. The scar burden constituted 35% of the total left ventricular mass, and the left ventricular ejection fraction was 19%. <b>*</b> indicates adherent thrombus within the ventricular lumen (cf <b>a</b>). Invasive coronary angiography showed 90% and 70% stenosis of the proximal left anterior descending and right coronary arteries, respectively. The patient subsequently underwent successful coronary artery bypass grafting and left ventricular aneurysmectomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g04c.jpeg" height="1540" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4c.</b>  Multivessel stenosis in a 75-year-old man who presented with congestive heart failure and syncope. The patient had experienced myocardial infarction 8 years earlier. An electrophysiologic study induced sustained monomorphic ventricular tachycardia requiring cardioversion. <b>(a)</b> Axial SSFP cine image shows severe thinning of the apical septum and apex consistent with an aneurysm. <b>*</b> indicates adherent thrombus within the ventricular lumen. <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis <b>(b)</b> and left anterior <b>(c)</b> oblique two-chamber inversion-recovery prepared gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images show extensive transmural enhancement involving the entire apex and anterior wall (arrows), a finding that is indicative of prior myocardial infarction. The scar burden constituted 35% of the total left ventricular mass, and the left ventricular ejection fraction was 19%. <b>*</b> indicates adherent thrombus within the ventricular lumen (cf <b>a</b>). Invasive coronary angiography showed 90% and 70% stenosis of the proximal left anterior descending and right coronary arteries, respectively. The patient subsequently underwent successful coronary artery bypass grafting and left ventricular aneurysmectomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F4C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g05a.jpeg" height="1649" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  Ischemic heart disease in a 53-year-old man with a 6-week history of worsening dyspnea who presented with sustained monomorphic ventricular tachycardia requiring electrical cardioversion. Coronary angiography showed only mild atherosclerotic disease, with approximately 40% stenosis of a ramus intermedius branch. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis oblique end-diastolic SSFP cine image shows marked thinning of the anteroseptum and anterior wall (arrows). Note the prominent trabeculation in the unaffected areas, most likely a postinfarction remodeling phenomenon. <b>(b, c)</b> Four-chamber <b>(b)</b> and two-chamber <b>(c)</b> inversion-recovery prepared gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images show extensive transmural infarction (arrowheads) involving the middle and apical anterior wall, the septum, and the entire apex. <b>*</b> indicates apical thrombus. The scar burden represented 37% of the total left ventricular mass, and the left ventricular ejection fraction was 29%. An implantable cardioverter defibrillator was subsequently inserted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g05b.jpeg" height="1636" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  Ischemic heart disease in a 53-year-old man with a 6-week history of worsening dyspnea who presented with sustained monomorphic ventricular tachycardia requiring electrical cardioversion. Coronary angiography showed only mild atherosclerotic disease, with approximately 40% stenosis of a ramus intermedius branch. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis oblique end-diastolic SSFP cine image shows marked thinning of the anteroseptum and anterior wall (arrows). Note the prominent trabeculation in the unaffected areas, most likely a postinfarc-tion remodeling phenomenon. <b>(b, c)</b> Four-chamber <b>(b)</b> and two-chamber <b>(c)</b> inversion-recovery prepared gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images show extensive transmural infarction (arrowheads) involving the middle and apical anterior wall, the septum, and the entire apex. <b>*</b> indicates apical thrombus. The scar burden represented 37% of the total left ventricular mass, and the left ventricular ejection fraction was 29%. An implantable cardioverter defibrillator was subsequently inserted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g05c.jpeg" height="1534" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5c.</b>  Ischemic heart disease in a 53-year-old man with a 6-week history of worsening dyspnea who presented with sustained monomorphic ventricular tachycardia requiring electrical cardioversion. Coronary angiography showed only mild atherosclerotic disease, with approximately 40% stenosis of a ramus intermedius branch. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis oblique end-diastolic SSFP cine image shows marked thinning of the anteroseptum and anterior wall (arrows). Note the prominent trabeculation in the unaffected areas, most likely a postinfarc-tion remodeling phenomenon. <b>(b, c)</b> Four-chamber <b>(b)</b> and two-chamber <b>(c)</b> inversion-recovery prepared gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images show extensive transmural infarction (arrowheads) involving the middle and apical anterior wall, the septum, and the entire apex. <b>*</b> indicates apical thrombus. The scar burden represented 37% of the total left ventricular mass, and the left ventricular ejection fraction was 29%. An implantable cardioverter defibrillator was subsequently inserted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F5C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g06a.jpeg" height="1684" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6a.</b>  Dilated cardiomyopathy in a 43-year-old man with a history of excess ethanol consumption who had collapsed secondary to monomorphic ventricular tachycardia. Invasive coronary angiographic findings were normal. <b>(a, b)</b> Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis oblique <b>(b)</b> SSFP images show dilatation primarily of the right ventricle, with focal thinning of the inferolateral wall of the left ventricle (arrow in <b>b</b>). The ejection fractions of the left and right ventricles were 25% and 18%, respectively. Note the concurrent pericardial and pleural effusions (<b>*</b>), findings that reflect increased atrial filling pressures. <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber SSFP image obtained superior to <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> shows a mass (arrows) adhering to the right atrial appendicular wall. <b>(d)</b> On a fat-saturated DIR-FSE T2-weighted MR image, the mass appears hyperintense. <b>(e)</b> On a dynamic perfusion gradient-echo MR image, the mass (arrows) is hypovascular. The mass was thought to represent thrombus. An implantable cardioverter defibrillator was inserted and anticoagulation therapy initiated.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F6A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g06b.jpeg" height="1676" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6b.</b>  Dilated cardiomyopathy in a 43-year-old man with a history of excess ethanol consumption who had collapsed secondary to monomorphic ventricular tachycardia. Invasive coronary angiographic findings were normal. <b>(a, b)</b> Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis oblique <b>(b)</b> SSFP images show dilatation primarily of the right ventricle, with focal thinning of the inferolateral wall of the left ventricle (arrow in <b>b</b>). The ejection fractions of the left and right ventricles were 25% and 18%, respectively. Note the concurrent pericardial and pleural effusions (<b>*</b>), findings that reflect increased atrial filling pressures. <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber SSFP image obtained superior to <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> shows a mass (arrows) adhering to the right atrial appendicular wall. <b>(d)</b> On a fat-saturated DIR-FSE T2-weighted MR image, the mass appears hyperintense. <b>(e)</b> On a dynamic perfusion gradient-echo MR image, the mass (arrows) is hypovascular. The mass was thought to represent thrombus. An implantable cardioverter defibrillator was inserted and anticoagulation therapy initiated.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F6B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g06c.jpeg" height="1709" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6c.</b>  Dilated cardiomyopathy in a 43-year-old man with a history of excess ethanol consumption who had collapsed secondary to monomorphic ventricular tachycardia. Invasive coronary angiographic findings were normal. <b>(a, b)</b> Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis oblique <b>(b)</b> SSFP images show dilatation primarily of the right ventricle, with focal thinning of the inferolateral wall of the left ventricle (arrow in <b>b</b>). The ejection fractions of the left and right ventricles were 25% and 18%, respectively. Note the concurrent pericardial and pleural effusions (<b>*</b>), findings that reflect increased atrial filling pressures. <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber SSFP image obtained superior to <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> shows a mass (arrows) adhering to the right atrial appendicular wall. <b>(d)</b> On a fat-saturated DIR-FSE T2-weighted MR image, the mass appears hyperintense. <b>(e)</b> On a dynamic perfusion gradient-echo MR image, the mass (arrows) is hypovascular. The mass was thought to represent thrombus. An implantable cardioverter defibrillator was inserted and anticoagulation therapy initiated.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F6C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g06d.jpeg" height="1703" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6d.</b>  Dilated cardiomyopathy in a 43-year-old man with a history of excess ethanol consumption who had collapsed secondary to monomorphic ventricular tachycardia. Invasive coronary angiographic findings were normal. <b>(a, b)</b> Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis oblique <b>(b)</b> SSFP images show dilatation primarily of the right ventricle, with focal thinning of the inferolateral wall of the left ventricle (arrow in <b>b</b>). The ejection fractions of the left and right ventricles were 25% and 18%, respectively. Note the concurrent pericardial and pleural effusions (<b>*</b>), findings that reflect increased atrial filling pressures. <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber SSFP image obtained superior to <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> shows a mass (arrows) adhering to the right atrial appendicular wall. <b>(d)</b> On a fat-saturated DIR-FSE T2-weighted MR image, the mass appears hyperintense. <b>(e)</b> On a dynamic perfusion gradient-echo MR image, the mass (arrows) is hypovascular. The mass was thought to represent thrombus. An implantable cardioverter defibrillator was inserted and anticoagulation therapy initiated.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F6D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g06e.jpeg" height="1800" width="1798" aria-labelledby="F6E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6e.</b>  Dilated cardiomyopathy in a 43-year-old man with a history of excess ethanol consumption who had collapsed secondary to monomorphic ventricular tachycardia. Invasive coronary angiographic findings were normal. <b>(a, b)</b> Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis oblique <b>(b)</b> SSFP images show dilatation primarily of the right ventricle, with focal thinning of the inferolateral wall of the left ventricle (arrow in <b>b</b>). The ejection fractions of the left and right ventricles were 25% and 18%, respectively. Note the concurrent pericardial and pleural effusions (<b>*</b>), findings that reflect increased atrial filling pressures. <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber SSFP image obtained superior to <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> shows a mass (arrows) adhering to the right atrial appendicular wall. <b>(d)</b> On a fat-saturated DIR-FSE T2-weighted MR image, the mass appears hyperintense. <b>(e)</b> On a dynamic perfusion gradient-echo MR image, the mass (arrows) is hypovascular. The mass was thought to represent thrombus. An implantable cardioverter defibrillator was inserted and anticoagulation therapy initiated.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F6E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g07a.jpeg" height="1575" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7a.</b>  Acute viral myocarditis in a 24-year-old man who presented with acute onset of central chest pain. The patient had a 5-day history of fever and myalgia. Twelve-lead ECG showed a 2-mm ST elevation in the inferolateral leads, with a peak troponin level of 47 μg/L. <b>(a, c</b>, <b>e)</b> Fat-saturated DIR-FSE T2-weighted MR images obtained at the basal <b>(a)</b>, mid- <b>(c)</b>, and apical <b>(e)</b> ventricular levels show multiple areas of high signal intensity affecting the epicardial portion of the basal and apical lateral and inferolateral walls (arrows) and the apical inferior wall. <b>(b, d</b>, <b>f)</b> Corresponding end systole short-axis oblique SSFP images do not show any associated reduction in systolic contraction. The edema that was evident on the T2-weighted images is seen as an area of increased epicardial signal intensity (<b>*</b>). The patient had positive serology test results for Epstein-Barr virus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F7A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g07b.jpeg" height="1582" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7b.</b>  Acute viral myocarditis in a 24-year-old man who presented with acute onset of central chest pain. The patient had a 5-day history of fever and myalgia. Twelve-lead ECG showed a 2-mm ST elevation in the inferolateral leads, with a peak troponin level of 47 μg/L. <b>(a, c</b>, <b>e)</b> Fat-saturated DIR-FSE T2-weighted MR images obtained at the basal <b>(a)</b>, mid- <b>(c)</b>, and apical <b>(e)</b> ventricular levels show multiple areas of high signal intensity affecting the epicardial portion of the basal and apical lateral and inferolateral walls (arrows) and the apical inferior wall. <b>(b, d</b>, <b>f)</b> Corresponding end systole short-axis oblique SSFP images do not show any associated reduction in systolic contraction. The edema that was evident on the T2-weighted images is seen as an area of increased epicardial signal intensity (<b>*</b>). The patient had positive serology test results for Epstein-Barr virus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F7B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g07c.jpeg" height="1600" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7c.</b>  Acute viral myocarditis in a 24-year-old man who presented with acute onset of central chest pain. The patient had a 5-day history of fever and myalgia. Twelve-lead ECG showed a 2-mm ST elevation in the inferolateral leads, with a peak troponin level of 47 μg/L. <b>(a, c</b>, <b>e)</b> Fat-saturated DIR-FSE T2-weighted MR images obtained at the basal <b>(a)</b>, mid- <b>(c)</b>, and apical <b>(e)</b> ventricular levels show multiple areas of high signal intensity affecting the epicardial portion of the basal and apical lateral and inferolateral walls (arrows) and the apical inferior wall. <b>(b, d</b>, <b>f)</b> Corresponding end systole short-axis oblique SSFP images do not show any associated reduction in systolic contraction. The edema that was evident on the T2-weighted images is seen as an area of increased epicardial signal intensity (<b>*</b>). The patient had positive serology test results for Epstein-Barr virus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F7C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g07d.jpeg" height="1588" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7d.</b>  Acute viral myocarditis in a 24-year-old man who presented with acute onset of central chest pain. The patient had a 5-day history of fever and myalgia. Twelve-lead ECG showed a 2-mm ST elevation in the inferolateral leads, with a peak troponin level of 47 μg/L. <b>(a, c</b>, <b>e)</b> Fat-saturated DIR-FSE T2-weighted MR images obtained at the basal <b>(a)</b>, mid- <b>(c)</b>, and apical <b>(e)</b> ventricular levels show multiple areas of high signal intensity affecting the epicardial portion of the basal and apical lateral and inferolateral walls (arrows) and the apical inferior wall. <b>(b, d</b>, <b>f)</b> Corresponding end systole short-axis oblique SSFP images do not show any associated reduction in systolic contraction. The edema that was evident on the T2-weighted images is seen as an area of increased epicardial signal intensity (<b>*</b>). The patient had positive serology test results for Epstein-Barr virus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F7D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g07e.jpeg" height="1520" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7e.</b>  Acute viral myocarditis in a 24-year-old man who presented with acute onset of central chest pain. The patient had a 5-day history of fever and myalgia. Twelve-lead ECG showed a 2-mm ST elevation in the inferolateral leads, with a peak troponin level of 47 μg/L. <b>(a, c</b>, <b>e)</b> Fat-saturated DIR-FSE T2-weighted MR images obtained at the basal <b>(a)</b>, mid- <b>(c)</b>, and apical <b>(e)</b> ventricular levels show multiple areas of high signal intensity affecting the epicardial portion of the basal and apical lateral and inferolateral walls (arrows) and the apical inferior wall. <b>(b, d</b>, <b>f)</b> Corresponding end systole short-axis oblique SSFP images do not show any associated reduction in systolic contraction. The edema that was evident on the T2-weighted images is seen as an area of increased epicardial signal intensity (<b>*</b>). The patient had positive serology test results for Epstein-Barr virus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F7E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7F" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g07f.jpeg" height="1498" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7F" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7f.</b>  Acute viral myocarditis in a 24-year-old man who presented with acute onset of central chest pain. The patient had a 5-day history of fever and myalgia. Twelve-lead ECG showed a 2-mm ST elevation in the inferolateral leads, with a peak troponin level of 47 μg/L. <b>(a, c</b>, <b>e)</b> Fat-saturated DIR-FSE T2-weighted MR images obtained at the basal <b>(a)</b>, mid- <b>(c)</b>, and apical <b>(e)</b> ventricular levels show multiple areas of high signal intensity affecting the epicardial portion of the basal and apical lateral and inferolateral walls (arrows) and the apical inferior wall. <b>(b, d</b>, <b>f)</b> Corresponding end systole short-axis oblique SSFP images do not show any associated reduction in systolic contraction. The edema that was evident on the T2-weighted images is seen as an area of increased epicardial signal intensity (<b>*</b>). The patient had positive serology test results for Epstein-Barr virus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F7F">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g08a.jpeg" height="1539" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8a.</b>  Chronic myocarditis in a 48-year-old woman who presented with supraventricular tachycardias and biventricular dysfunction. Invasive angiography demonstrated normal coronary arteries. <b>(a)</b> Diastolic short-axis oblique SSFP image shows areas of severe thinning that affect the septum and inferior wall (arrows). <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis oblique inversion-recovery gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images obtained at different mid-ventricular levels show transmural scarring that affects the interventricular septum and the inferior and lateral wall (arrowheads). Note also the extensive involvement of the right ventricle. Biventricular dysfunction was seen, with a left ventricular ejection fraction of 26.7% and a right ventricular ejection fraction of 37%. Subsequent right ventricular endomyocardial biopsy demonstrated patchy endocardial fibrosis and myocyte hypertrophy with interstitial inflammatory infiltrates, findings that are all suggestive of postinflammatory dilated cardiomyopathy with evidence of ongoing active myocarditis. Because of the extensive biventricular involvement and associated risk of sudden death, an implantable cardioverter defibrillator was inserted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F8A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g08b.jpeg" height="1552" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8b.</b>  Chronic myocarditis in a 48-year-old woman who presented with supraventricular tachycardias and biventricular dysfunction. Invasive angiography demonstrated normal coronary arteries. <b>(a)</b> Diastolic short-axis oblique SSFP image shows areas of severe thinning that affect the septum and inferior wall (arrows). <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis oblique inversion-recovery gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images obtained at different mid-ventricular levels show transmural scarring that affects the interventricular septum and the inferior and lateral wall (arrowheads). Note also the extensive involvement of the right ventricle. Biventricular dysfunction was seen, with a left ventricular ejection fraction of 26.7% and a right ventricular ejection fraction of 37%. Subsequent right ventricular endomyocardial biopsy demonstrated patchy endocardial fibrosis and myocyte hypertrophy with interstitial inflammatory infiltrates, findings that are all suggestive of postinflammatory dilated cardiomyopathy with evidence of ongoing active myocarditis. Because of the extensive biventricular involvement and associated risk of sudden death, an implantable cardioverter defibrillator was inserted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F8B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g08c.jpeg" height="1498" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8c.</b>  Chronic myocarditis in a 48-year-old woman who presented with supraventricular tachycardias and biventricular dysfunction. Invasive angiography demonstrated normal coronary arteries. <b>(a)</b> Diastolic short-axis oblique SSFP image shows areas of severe thinning that affect the septum and inferior wall (arrows). <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis oblique inversion-recovery gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images obtained at different mid-ventricular levels show transmural scarring that affects the interventricular septum and the inferior and lateral wall (arrowheads). Note also the extensive involvement of the right ventricle. Biventricular dysfunction was seen, with a left ventricular ejection fraction of 26.7% and a right ventricular ejection fraction of 37%. Subsequent right ventricular endomyocardial biopsy demonstrated patchy endocardial fibrosis and myocyte hypertrophy with interstitial inflammatory infiltrates, findings that are all suggestive of postinflammatory dilated cardiomyopathy with evidence of ongoing active myocarditis. Because of the extensive biventricular involvement and associated risk of sudden death, an implantable cardioverter defibrillator was inserted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F8C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g09a.jpeg" height="1570" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9a.</b>  Infectious myocarditis in a 45-year-old man with known Chagas disease who experienced a number of presyncopal episodes secondary to self-terminating runs of ventricular tachycardia. <b>(a, b)</b> Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis oblique <b>(b)</b> inversion-recovery gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images show an aneurysm, along with marked thinning and hyperenhancement of the myocardium in the affected area of the midventricular lateral wall (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Curved reformatted image from a contrast-enhanced ECG-gated multidetector CT coronary angiographic study shows a normal left circumflex artery. The remainder of the coronary arteries were also normal. The patient underwent successful ablation of an arrhythmogenic focus, completed treatment for Chagas disease, and remains well.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F9A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g09b.jpeg" height="1586" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9b.</b>  Infectious myocarditis in a 45-year-old man with known Chagas disease who experienced a number of presyncopal episodes secondary to self-terminating runs of ventricular tachycardia. <b>(a, b)</b> Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis oblique <b>(b)</b> inversion-recovery gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images show an aneurysm, along with marked thinning and hyperenhancement of the myocardium in the affected area of the midventricular lateral wall (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Curved reformatted image from a contrast-enhanced ECG-gated multidetector CT coronary angiographic study shows a normal left circumflex artery. The remainder of the coronary arteries were also normal. The patient underwent successful ablation of an arrhythmogenic focus, completed treatment for Chagas disease, and remains well.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F9B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g09c.jpeg" height="1590" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9c.</b>  Infectious myocarditis in a 45-year-old man with known Chagas disease who experienced a number of presyncopal episodes secondary to self-terminating runs of ventricular tachycardia. <b>(a, b)</b> Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis oblique <b>(b)</b> inversion-recovery gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images show an aneurysm, along with marked thinning and hyperenhancement of the myocardium in the affected area of the midventricular lateral wall (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Curved reformatted image from a contrast-enhanced ECG-gated multidetector CT coronary angiographic study shows a normal left circumflex artery. The remainder of the coronary arteries were also normal. The patient underwent successful ablation of an arrhythmogenic focus, completed treatment for Chagas disease, and remains well.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F9C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g10a.jpeg" height="1535" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10a.</b>  Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 40-year-old man who presented with bradycardia secondary to third-degree heart block. Invasive coronary angiography revealed normal coronary arteries, and transthoracic echocardiographic findings were reported as unremarkable. <b>(a, b)</b> Short-axis oblique SSFP images show focal nodular thickening of the basal (arrows in <b>a</b>) and midanterior (arrows in <b>b</b>) septum and right ventricular free wall. <b>(c, d)</b> Corresponding short-axis oblique inversion-recovery gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images show diffuse delayed enhancement in the affected areas (arrows). Scattered peribronchovascular nodules in the right upper lobe associated with extensive mediastinal lymphadenopathy were noted at chest CT. Results of trans-bronchial biopsy confirmed the presence of noncaseating granuloma in keeping with sarcoidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F10A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g10b.jpeg" height="1540" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10b.</b>  Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 40-year-old man who presented with bradycardia secondary to third-degree heart block. Invasive coronary angiography revealed normal coronary arteries, and transthoracic echocardiographic findings were reported as unremarkable. <b>(a, b)</b> Short-axis oblique SSFP images show focal nodular thickening of the basal (arrows in <b>a</b>) and midanterior (arrows in <b>b</b>) septum and right ventricular free wall. <b>(c, d)</b> Corresponding short-axis oblique inversion-recovery gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images show diffuse delayed enhancement in the affected areas (arrows). Scattered peribronchovascular nodules in the right upper lobe associated with extensive mediastinal lymphadenopathy were noted at chest CT. Results of trans-bronchial biopsy confirmed the presence of noncaseating granuloma in keeping with sarcoidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F10B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g10c.jpeg" height="1541" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10c.</b>  Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 40-year-old man who presented with bradycardia secondary to third-degree heart block. Invasive coronary angiography revealed normal coronary arteries, and transthoracic echocardiographic findings were reported as unremarkable. <b>(a, b)</b> Short-axis oblique SSFP images show focal nodular thickening of the basal (arrows in <b>a</b>) and midanterior (arrows in <b>b</b>) septum and right ventricular free wall. <b>(c, d)</b> Corresponding short-axis oblique inversion-recovery gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images show diffuse delayed enhancement in the affected areas (arrows). Scattered peribronchovascular nodules in the right upper lobe associated with extensive mediastinal lymphadenopathy were noted at chest CT. Results of trans-bronchial biopsy confirmed the presence of noncaseating granuloma in keeping with sarcoidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F10C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g10d.jpeg" height="1522" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10d.</b>  Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 40-year-old man who presented with bradycardia secondary to third-degree heart block. Invasive coronary angiography revealed normal coronary arteries, and transthoracic echocar-diographic findings were reported as unremarkable. <b>(a, b)</b> Short-axis oblique SSFP images show focal nodular thickening of the basal (arrows in <b>a</b>) and midanterior (arrows in <b>b</b>) septum and right ventricular free wall. <b>(c, d)</b> Corresponding short-axis oblique inversion-recovery gradient-echo T1-weighted MR images show diffuse delayed enhancement in the affected areas (arrows). Scattered peribronchovascular nodules in the right upper lobe associated with extensive mediastinal lymphadenopathy were noted at chest CT. Results of trans-bronchial biopsy confirmed the presence of noncaseating granuloma in keeping with sarcoidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F10D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g11a.jpeg" height="1675" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Cardiac amyloidosis in a 75-year-old man with exertional dyspnea. Echocardiography showed diffuse left ventricular hypertrophy but did not demonstrate electrical changes attributable to hypertrophy. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber SSFP image shows symmetric left ventricular thickening. Note also the nodular thickening of the interatrial septum (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Resting dynamic perfusion cine gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows a circumferential subendocardial perfusion defect (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Subsequent gadolinium-enhanced four-chamber inversion-recovery prepared gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows delayed enhancement in the left atrium and interatrial septum (arrowheads), the right ventricular free wall, the left ventricular sub-endocardial septum (arrows), and the lateral wall. Note the characteristic low signal intensity of the blood pool, likely reflecting significant organ uptake of gadolinium. Cardiac amyloidosis was confirmed with endocardial biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g11b.jpeg" height="1692" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Cardiac amyloidosis in a 75-year-old man with exertional dyspnea. Echocardiography showed diffuse left ventricular hypertrophy but did not demonstrate electrical changes attributable to hypertrophy. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber SSFP image shows symmetric left ventricular thickening. Note also the nodular thickening of the interatrial septum (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Resting dynamic perfusion cine gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows a circumferential subendocardial perfusion defect (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Subsequent gadolinium-enhanced four-chamber inversion-recovery prepared gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows delayed enhancement in the left atrium and interatrial septum (arrowheads), the right ventricular free wall, the left ventricular sub-endocardial septum (arrows), and the lateral wall. Note the characteristic low signal intensity of the blood pool, likely reflecting significant organ uptake of gadolinium. Cardiac amyloidosis was confirmed with endocardial biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12g11c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11c.</b>  Cardiac amyloidosis in a 75-year-old man with exertional dyspnea. Echocardiography showed diffuse left ventricular hypertrophy but did not demonstrate electrical changes attributable to hypertrophy. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber SSFP image shows symmetric left ventricular thickening. Note also the nodular thickening of the interatrial septum (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Resting dynamic perfusion cine gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows a circumferential subendocardial perfusion defect (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Subsequent gadolinium-enhanced four-chamber inversion-recovery prepared gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows delayed enhancement in the left atrium and interatrial septum (arrowheads), the right ventricular free wall, the left ventricular sub-endocardial septum (arrows), and the lateral wall. Note the characteristic low signal intensity of the blood pool, likely reflecting significant organ uptake of gadolinium. Cardiac amyloidosis was confirmed with endocardial biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085715&amp;id=F11C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T1" class="table"><figcaption><b>Table 1.</b> <b>Causes of Sudden Cardiac Death</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12t01x.jpeg" height="1123" width="1800" aria-labelledby="T1" loading="lazy" /><div class="notes"><div role="doc-footnote"><div role="paragraph"><b>*</b>Percentages are based on pooled data from references 1, 3, 5, and 8.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup><b>†</b></sup>These conditions account for a greater proportion (20%–25%) of sudden cardiac deaths in patients under 35 years of age and in athletes.</div></div></div></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T2" class="table"><figcaption><b>Table 2.</b> <b>Diagnostic Strengths of Cardiac MR Imaging and ECG-gated Multidetector CT in Evaluating Specific Heart Diseases</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12t02x.jpeg" height="821" width="1800" aria-labelledby="T2" loading="lazy" /><div class="notes"><div role="doc-footnote">Note.—CAD = coronary artery disease, DCM = dilated cardiomyopathy, LV = left ventricular.</div></div></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T3" class="table"><figcaption><b>Table 3.</b> <b>Japanese Ministry of Health and Welfare Guidelines for Diagnosing Cardiac Sarcoidosis</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085715/asset/images/g09ma12t03x.jpeg" height="443" width="1800" aria-labelledby="T3" loading="lazy" /><div class="notes"><div role="doc-footnote"><div role="paragraph">Source.—Reference 50.</div><div role="paragraph"><b>*</b>ECG abnormality + histologic diagnosis of extracardiac sarcoidosis + additional finding obtained with one of the other modalities listed in the table = diagnosis of cardiac sarcoidosis.</div></div></div></figure></div><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Myerburg</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">RJ</span></span>, Kessler KM, Castellanos A. Sudden cardiac death: epidemiology, transient risk, and intervention assessment. <em>Ann Intern Med</em>1993; 119: 1187–1197.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.7326/0003-4819-119-12-199312150-00006">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8239250/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Ann+Intern+Med&amp;publication_year=1993&amp;pages=1187&amp;doi=10.7326%2F0003-4819-119-12-199312150-00006&amp;pmid=8239250">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="R2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Myerburg</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">RJ</span></span>, Castellanos A. Cardiac arrest and sudden cardiac death. Philadelphia, Pa: Saunders, 2001.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=MyerburgRJ%2C+Castellanos+A.+Cardiac+arrest+and+sudden+cardiac+death.+Philadelphia%2C+Pa%3A+Saunders%2C+2001.">Google Scholar</a></div